name: hexyl silane
Reason: The structure of hexyl silane consists of a hexyl group (a six-carbon chain) attached to a silane group (SiH3). To predict the melting point, we consider the effects of both groups separately. The simplest silane, silane (SiH4), has a melting point of -185°C. Adding alkyl chains typically increases the melting point due to an increase in terms of van der Waals forces between the molecules. Since the carbon chain has six carbons, the molecular weight and surface area are relatively large, contributing significantly to the melting point increase. Each -CH2 group in an alkane generally adds about 20°C when comparing homologous series of hydrocarbons. Therefore, the effect of six additional -CH2 groups from the hexyl chain would give an increase of about 120°C to the base value of silane's melting point.
